# HyperSocial Sales Call Flow — Master Guide

*Synthesized from 5 ideal call transcripts. Reps: Braden Wallake, Liz McCalister. Prospects: David Yankelewitz, Trent Lee, Carlos Fuentes, David Bornhorst, Blair Koch.*

---

## Overview

HyperSocial sells a **$2,500 one-time build** that sets up a prospect's full LinkedIn outreach system over 30 days. The recurring cost after the build is ~$200/month ($99 software + ~$100 Sales Navigator). Optional managed services range from $500–$2,000/month depending on scope.

The sales call is **consultative and conversational** — never pitchy. The rep's job is to understand the prospect's situation, reflect it back, and let the product sell itself through the fit. Every call in this collection closed or moved to a clear next step.

---

## Stage 1 — Rapport & Small Talk (0–3 min)

**Goal:** Lower guard, establish human connection before any business talk.

**What works:**
- Comment on something visible (location, weather, their background, a sweater)
- Share something personal about yourself first (Braden's Mexico story came up on multiple calls naturally)
- Keep it light and genuine — don't rush past this stage

**Examples from transcripts:**
- *"How's spring coming along?"* → led to a 2-minute weather conversation that warmed up Trent Lee immediately
- Braden and David Bornhorst spent several minutes on Columbus neighborhoods and Ohio real estate before a single business question was asked
- Liz and Blair bonded over AirPods, Michigan, and Denver weather

**Key principle:** The prospect needs to like you before they'll trust you with their business. Don't skip this.

---

## Stage 2 — Discovery Opening (3–8 min)

**Goal:** Understand why they're on the call and what's not working. Let them talk.

### The Opening Question

Every rep opened with a version of one of these:

- *"What made you want to schedule this?"* (Braden)
- *"Why are you currently looking for something for lead generation?"* (Liz)
- *"What have you been doing in the past that has brought new customers in, and why now are you looking for a new route?"* (Liz to Blair)

**Never start with the pitch. Always start with a question.**

### What You're Listening For

- Current lead gen methods (referrals, networking, events, cold email, etc.)
- Why those methods aren't enough (unpredictable, time-consuming, not scaling)
- Capacity situation (solo operator? small team? too busy to prospect?)
- Geography and target audience
- Whether they've tried LinkedIn tools before

### Common Discovery Patterns Across All 5 Calls

| Pain | How It Was Expressed |
|------|----------------------|
| Referral dependency | "Most of my business is referral-based, which is great, but very unpredictable." (Carlos) |
| Too busy to prospect | "I'm a one-man shop. Marketing takes a backseat." (Carlos) |
| Not enough pipeline | "I just don't have enough clients. I'm not getting enough meetings." (David Y.) |
| Outbound feels overwhelming | "The last hat people put on is the prospecting hat." (Braden's reflection of Trent) |
| Prior LinkedIn tool that stopped working | "We were seeing the leads kind of drop off." (Trent) |
| Growth ceiling | "I literally hit my ceiling — I was booking clients into July." (Trent) |

### Discovery Follow-Up Questions

Once they've explained their situation, dig deeper with:

- *"Ideally, would you like to get leads for both [X and Y]?"* — used when multiple ICPs emerge
- *"How many new clients are you looking to bring in monthly? What would move the needle for you?"*
- *"Is that more B2B or B2C?"*
- *"Tell me about your average customer."*
- *"Are you thinking of building locally, nationally, or both?"*

**Listen for multiple ICPs.** Trent had Vistage + advisory. Blair had TAB boards + StratPro. Carlos had direct clients + referral partners. This matters for how you structure the campaigns later.

---

## Stage 3 — Transition & Credibility Bridge (8–12 min)

**Goal:** Connect their pain to your solution without launching into a full pitch. Establish that you understand their world.

### The Credibility Bridge

Before pitching, demonstrate that you've worked with people like them:

- *"We've worked with 65 TAB owners to date — corporate now pays for new franchisee owners to work with us because the results have been so great."* (Braden to Trent)
- *"Consultants and coaches are a big client base for us."* (Liz to Blair)
- *"That's exactly the revenue range our ideal client falls into for ourselves internally."* (Braden to David B., on the $500K–$10M range)

**If they've tried LinkedIn tools before:** Acknowledge the change.
- *"You are very correct that LinkedIn has changed a lot."*
- Explain why HyperSocial is different — quality over volume, human-written messaging, proprietary software built internally.

### Reflect Their Pain Back

Before explaining the product, summarize what you heard:

- *"You're wearing enough hats. The last hat people usually put on is the prospecting hat."*
- *"You come in at about the same spot most people come to us — I've got referrals, I think LinkedIn is right for me, but where do I start?"*
- *"Smart. Because that means when referrals slow down, you have something backing them up."*

This shows you were listening and makes the prospect feel understood before you ask them to listen to you.

